Principles 1

What is prediction?

  • Have one or many dependent (or target) variables
  • Have one or many features
    • These are characteristics of the unit that we will use to predict the dependent variable
    • We do not care whether the features cause the dependent variable, or merely reflect the true causes
    • The idea is to build a model that relates our features to our dependent variable.

Principles: The golden rules of prediction

  • When building your model, only use features that will be known before you know the value of the dependent variable.
  • Only try to predict what can be predicted. Don't try to predict equilibria: you will go mad.
  • Make your model generalisable. Cross validate.
  • Time spent on features is more valuable than time spent on algorithms.

Principles: The Rabee Tourky edit

Pop quiz

  1. Name a predictive problem
  2. What would be a good feature in a model for the problem?
  3. What method would you use now?
  4. Is the problem predictable?

Principles: Parametric approaches & data generating processes

  • Your model has a fixed number of parameters; using it, you can generate new observations y.
    • if you can generate new draws of both y and X, this is called a generative model
  • When to use?
    • When you have lots of confounding unobserved/biased data
    • When you are concerned about modelling uncertainty
  • Tools: Probability theory & statistics

Principles: An example of a data generating process

# Define some parameters
a <- 5
b <- 3
c <- 6
sigma <- 4

# Create some features
x1 <- rnorm(100)
x2 <- sample(c(0,1), 100, replace = T)

# "Generate" your data
y <- rnorm(100, # Sample size
           a + b*x1 + c*x2, # The conditional mean
           sigma) # The standard deviation (this can be conditional also)
plot.ts(y)

Principles: An example of a data generating process

What we have

  • some of y, and all of x1 and x2

What we want to do

  • Estimate a, b and c
  • Use our estimates + the complete x1 and x2 to estimate the missing parts of y

We'll come back to this example in a minute

Principles: Non-parametetric approaches

  • The number of parameters in the model grows with the amount of data
  • Try to pull out interesting non-linearities and other patterns.
  • You can't write out a data generating process.
  • Generally perform better at prediction, but aren't so good for dealing with bias/confounding or uncertainty.
  • Tools: Math and computer science.

Principles: Modelling paradigms

  • Linear models and their flavours
  • Support vector machines
  • Tree-based algorithms
  • Neural networks and their flavours
  • Many others!

A quick background on probability distributions

These are mathematical formulae which serve three main purposes:

  • Give us an idea of the relatively likelihood of an observation;
  • Allow us to generate fake data to summarise uncertainty;
  • Allow hypothesis testing.

Distributions are defined by parameters

Two normal distributions:

  • Black: Mean = 0, standard deviation = 2
  • Red: Mean = 2, standard deviation = 3

Distributions are defined by parameters

Time to generate some random data

number <- 5
mean <- 2, 
sd <- 2
x <- rnorm(number, mean, sd)
hist(x)

Try playing with the number of observations and parameter values. What happens?

Distributions use probabilistic notation

Time to learn some notation. When we are talking about y having a normal distribution with mean 0 and standard deviation 1, we say

y(0,1)

For a general mean and standard deviation, we say

y(,)

where is mu and is sigma.

Linear models

Very simple, and very powerful.

Start from the simplest example:

variable=mean+deviation from mean

which we write as

yi=+i

The (mu) is the intercept and does not vary for each individual, which is why it has no i subscript. We typically use (epsilon) to denote model residuals.

Linear models

  • In order for this to be a generative model, we need to make a distributional assumption about .
    • For many cases, people use a normal distribution, with mean 0 and a standard deviation (sigma).
    • So yi=+i and (0,)
    • In R: y <- mu + rnorm(100, 0, sigma)

Since adding a number to every element of a distribution only changes its mean we can write the model in probabilistic notation as:

yi(,)

Linear models

  • The parameters and from the simple linear model described above can be estimated using a method called Ordinary Least Squares
mu <- 5
sigma <- 2
y <- mu + rnorm(200, 0, sigma)

model <- lm(y ~ 1)
#summary(model) # This tells you the parameter estimates

A slightly more complex model

This exercise should help you understand the linear model as a conditional mean model. That is, our predicted values are the average of y conditional on X. What would this model look like in probabilistic notation?

yi=+1x1,i+2x2,i+3x3,i+i

A slightly more complex model: R syntax

If both your dependent variable depvar and your features live in a dataframe yourdataframe, then you can use

mod2 <- lm(depvar ~ Feature1 + Feature2 + Feature3 + etc, data = yourdataframe)

If you want to use all features in your dataframe, use

mod2 <- lm(depvar ~ ., data = yourdataframe)

Exercise: Predicting out of sample

  • Generate three random features with 1000 observations
  • Specify an intercept, three slope parameters, and a standard deviation
  • Use your DGP to generate a new variable Y
  • Put all four variables in a data frame
  • Create a new variable called Y1. For the first 500 observations, it is the same as Y, and NA after.
    • (You may want to split it into two dataframes)
  • Build a linear model of Y1 given x1, x2 and x3
  • Use the model to generate predictions of the missing Y1. How far off are they?

A note on R squared

  • This describes the proportion of variance in Y explained by X in sample
    • An upper-bound estimate of the predictive power of the model.
    • When used for models of trending variables, is completely invalid
    • Always need to evaluate model fit out of sample

Exercise: what happens to R2 when you add more features?

Overfitting

Because in-sample model fit improves with more features, you may be tempted to add more.

  • Can result in poor out-of-sample performance
  • We call this failure to generalise
  • Make sure you evaluate fit on a test-set of data that you did not use to generate the model
  • Doing this repeatedly in order to choose tuning parameters & features is called cross validation
    • Nowadays, this is automated in many packages.

Thinking about features

  • Must be known at the point that a prediction is being made
    • Many, many times I have seen models predicting yt given $x_{t}, or worse, xt+1.
  • If you can't think of a theoretical reason for a feature to be included, don't include it.
  • Construct features! Use theory to guide this.
    • Time trends
    • Decaying time trends
    • Polynomials on things like age, etc.
  • Use your new database joining skills to import features from elsewhere.
  • Interactions are important, but not too many.

Under the likelihood

How are the parameters being estimated?

  • In the lm function, by matrix algebra.
  • In general, by maximum likelihood. Knowing something about ML will help you trust the models and understand the limitations.

Back to density

Let's say I have a y variable that looks like this, and a proposed linear model of:

yi=+xi+i

which is just yi(+xi,)

x <- rnorm(20)
mu <- 5
beta <- 2
sigma <- 4
y <- rnorm(20, mu + beta*x, sigma)
hist(x, xlim = c(min(x)-5, max(x)+5), prob = T)

Back to density

Back to density

I take a stab at guessing the parameters, say, mu=5, =1 and =5

Likelihood

  • For every data point in y, take the height of the curve given your current parameter estimates
  • The likelihood is the product of all the densities for all yi values.
    • idensity(y|,,)
    • What is 0.3 * 0.3?
    • What is (0.3)20? How about (0.3)n?
    • We typically take logs of the densities to avoid floating point issues

Maximum Likelihood

  • The log of the density turns the product into a sum:
    • Likelihood(y|,,)=ilog(density(yi|,,))
    • This is a single number
  • What a computer does is works out which parameters maximise the likelihood
    • Chooses and to minimise the negative log likelihood
    • Uses something like gradient descent
  • The ratio of likelihoods for two models is very useful for model comparison!

A quick note on modelling binary variables

Let's say y takes two values: 1 if a customer makes a purchase, and 0 otherwise.

Problem

  • In a linear model, the fitted values of Y are not bounded by 0 and 1.
  • Can lead do big problems in generating predictions and making inference.

A quick note on modelling binary variables

Solution

The logit and probit models take the fitted values of y and transform them from an unbounded scale onto a bounded scale. 

example_model <- glm(binarvar ~ feature1 + feature2 + ..., data = mydataframe, )

Putting it all together: Regularised GLMs

Problem:

  • Including more variables can help & hinder out-of-sample performance.
    • help Because you're using more information to make predictions
    • hinder because you may be picking up spurious correlations.
    • Need to include the right variables.

Putting it all together: Regularised GLMs

A solution

  • Each variable has to pay to play. Those that do not help improve predictions drop out first.
  • As the size of the blind increases, only the best variables are left.
  • This is called regularisation.

Putting it all together: Regularised GLMs

LASSO

  • The Blind is either the length of the vector (Euclidian norm)
    • The more parameters included, the bigger the penalty.

Ridge Regression

  • Here, the penalty is the squared length of the vector.

So choose to maximise

likelihood(y|)+cost()

Putting it all together: Regularised GLMs

library(glmnet)
# Note: Make sure no missing values in any of your dependent or independent variables
Y <- yourdataframe$yourdependentvariable
X <- model.matrix(~ Feature1 + Feature2 + etc, data = yourdataframe)

mod1 <- glmnet(x = X, y = Y)
plot(mod1)

Putting it all together: Regularised GLMs

# We generally want to cross-validate model to choose lambda
library(doParallel) # in Windows, library(doMC)
mod2 <- cv.glmnet(x = X, y = Y, nfolds = 10, parallel = T)
plot(mod2)
y_predicted <- predict(mod2, s = "lambda.min")
